Jameron also asked, "How do we know that this kind of operation is valid?"
This question gets a little deeper into the mathematical idea behind it. In algebra, we work with expressions that can contain constants, variables, and arithmetic operations. The operation we applied in the problem, $2(399)$, is called distributive property (multiplication over addition).
The distributive property says that for any real numbers $a$, $b$, and $c$, the equation $(a+b)\times c$ is equal to $a\times c+b\times c$. So, the equation $2(21)(19)$ is equivalent to $2\times 21\times 19$. This is because we are multiplying each term in the addition separately.
The rule of this distributive property can be generalized to any expression $(a_{1}+a_{2}+...+a_{n})\times c$, where $n$ is any integer greater than or equal to $1$. This means that we can always distribute multiplication over any addition of constants, variables, or terms.
Think of the addition as a bundle of sticks, and the multiplication as a force that acts on each of the sticks separately. If we multiply each stick in the bundle by a force, the total force will be the sum of the forces acting on each stick. The distributive property shows us how this force works.
